<assessment id="u4_m3_cq2_tutor2">
    <title>Tutor</title>
    <page>
    <question id="q1">
        <body>A publishing company wanted to test whether typing speeds differ when using word
                processor A or word processor B. A random sample of 25
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T133009-0500"?>typists<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T133007-0500" content="secretaries"?>
                was selected and the typing speed (in words per minute)
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T133020-0500"?>was<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T133019-0500" content="were"?>
                recorded for each
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T133140-0500"?>typist<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T133137-0500" content="secretary"?>
                when using word processor A and when using word processor B. (Which word processor
                is used first is determined for each
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T133152-0500"?>typist<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T133150-0500" content="secretary"?>
                by a coin flip).
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T133057-0500"?>Which "case"
                does this study fall into?<?oxy_insert_end?></body>
        <multiple_choice shuffle="false">
            <choice value="A">Comparing two
                    means<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T133225-0500"?>&#8212;<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T133159-0500" content=" - "?>independent
                    samples</choice>
            <choice value="B">Comparing two
                    means<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T133232-0500"?>&#8212;<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T133228-0500" content=" - "?>matched
                    pairs</choice>
            <choice value="C">Comparing more than two
                    means<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T133238-0500"?>&#8212;<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T133237-0500" content=" - "?>independent
                    samples</choice>
        </multiple_choice>
        <part>
            <response match="A">
                <feedback>Incorrect. While it is true that this example calls for
                        comparing two means (the mean typing speed of the two word processors), note
                        that each
                        <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T133313-0500"?>typist<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T133310-0500" content="secretary"?>
                        was measured twice.</feedback>
            </response>
            <response match="B" score="10">
                <feedback>Good
                        <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T133254-0500"?>j<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T133253-0500" content="J"?>ob!
                        Indeed, this example calls for comparing two means (the mean typing speeds
                        of the two word processors), and since each
                        <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T133320-0500"?>typist<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T133318-0500" content="secretary"?>
                        is measured twice, this is an example of matched pairs.</feedback>
            </response>
            <response match="C">
                <feedback>Incorrect. Note that we are comparing only two word
                        processors here, and in addition, each
                        <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T133329-0500"?>typist<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T133327-0500" content="secretary"?>
                        was measured twice. </feedback>
            </response>
        </part>
    </question></page>
  
</assessment>
